- **Spatial Channel Downsampling**: splits downsampling into 2 steps (pointwise & depthwise conv) → less info loss

  - Solution: decouple these operations (use a pointwise conv to modulate channel dimn and depthwise conv for spatial downsampling)  
  - It wants to:  
    - **Shrink the picture size** (so H×W → H/2 × W/2, fewer pixels).

    - **Pointwise convolution (1×1)**  
      - Only changes the **channels (C → 2C)**.  
      - It doesn’t touch the height/width.

    - **Depthwise convolution (3×3 stride=2)**  
      - Only reduces the **height/width (H×W → H/2×W/2)**.  
      - It keeps channels separate, so each channel has its own tiny filter.

Old way: **big 3×3 conv that touches all channels at once** → expensive, many parameters.

New way: **1×1 conv for channels \+ 3×3 depthwise for size** → way fewer multiplications.

- If they’re already similar, the cost is low (good prediction) If they’re very different, the cost is high
